04406nam a22005775i 9780774817585DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20112010xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748175857 a10.59962/97807748175852doi  a(DE-B1597)661345  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aDS897.K61257bE34 2010eb 7aSOC0150002bisacsh04a307.1/216095218741 aEdgington, David W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReconstructing Kobe :bThe Geography of Crisis and Opportunity /cDavid W. Edgington. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2011] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b45 b&w photos, 21 maps, 28 charts, 27 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tGlossary of Japanese Terms -- tIntroduction -- tEarthquakes and Urban Reconstruction -- tKobe and the Hanshin Earthquake -- tThe Planning and Reconstruction Response -- tProtest, Participation, and the Phoenix Plan -- tNeighbourhood Case Studies -- tSymbolic Projects and the Local Economy -- tConclusions -- tChronology of the Ten-Year Reconstruction Period in Kobe Following the Hanshin Earthquake (1995–2005) -- tNational Government Relief and Recovery Measures, 1995 -- tMajor Reconstruction Actions Taken by Local Government in 1995 -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSix thousand people died and hundreds of thousands lost their homes when an earthquake hit Kobe in January 1995. The Hanshin Earthquake was the largest disaster to affect postwar Japan and one of the most destructive postwar natural disasters to strike a developed country. Although the media focused on the disaster's immediate effects, the long-term reconstruction efforts have gone largely unexplored. Based on fieldwork and interviews with planners, activists, and bureaucrats, Reconstructing Kobe records the first ten years of reconstruction and recovery and offers detailed descriptions of the geography of crisis and opportunity. Which districts were most vulnerable to the quake and why? Did planners successfully exploit opportunities to revitalize the city and make it more sustainable and disaster proof? David Edgington's intricate investigation of one of the largest redevelopments in recent history offers a compelling post-disaster case study for planners and policy makers and is essential reading for students and scholars of Japanese urban and planning history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCity planningzJapanzKōbe-shi. 0aKobe Earthquake, Japan, 1995. 0aLand usezJapanzKōbe-shi. 0aMunicipal governmentzJapanzKōbe-shi. 0aUrban renewalzJapanzKōbe-shixHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Geography.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077481758540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774817585423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774817585/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles